Author Name: **Stefan Ludwig**
Original Redmine Message: 1145 from https://www.veripool.org



---

Hi again

It does not seem to be possible to have a task consume time. E.g., if I wanted to drive my simulation with bus cycles, I could implement this in Verilog with

```
export "DPI-C" task write_reg;

task write_reg(input int addr, input int data);
begin
  bus_adr = addr;
  bus_data = data;
  bus_write = 1;
  @(posedge clk)
  bus_write = 0;
endtask;

```

and things would work as expected. Now, since I have to drive clk inside the main cpp,  I understand that this code is hard/impossible to translate, but is there a way in Verilator to do that?

And if not, how do people create bus transactors in an elegant way? I could carry around some state in cpp, and call a function to wiggle the wires accordingly, when time is at x, and unset the wires (write in the above example) at time x+2, but it's kind of cumbersome and it would be more elegant and compatible with other simulators, if it could be done inside tasks.

Cheers,

Stefan

